Economics 301 Midterm Exam

Allocation: Specifies an amount of each good that each person gets
* feasible if doesn’t give out more goods than are in the economy

Edgeworth Box: Dimensions of the box show total amounts of each good

Pareto Efficient: An allocation is pareto efficient if there is no way to make one person better off without hurting someone else

Efficient Allocations: MRS_A = MRS_B
* All gains from trades are exhausted - cant make one better off without hurting the other

Contract Curve: Connects Pareto Efficient allocations
* After trading, all final allocations will be on this curve

General Equilibrium
* Only relative prices matter (P_x / P_y) since there is no money
* In equilibrium, there is no excess demand or supply for either good
* Solving:
    * Only relative prices matter — set P_y = 1
    * Calculate I_A and I_B (value of endowments)
    * Equilibrium, so set total demand = total supply for good x, solve for P_x
    * FInd equilibrium allocation using demand functions

Production
* Two goods (x, y) and two factors of production (L, K)
* L, K are in fixed supply, how much should we use to produce x and y?
* Producer either good has a marginal cost, ratio is MRT = MC_x / MC_y
* MRT is marginal rate of transformation, the rate we can substitute between output of x and y
* MRS_A = MRS_B = MRT is efficiency

First Welfare Theorem: Competitive equilibrium results in a Pareto Efficient allocation
* Each consumer is maximizing utility
    * MRS_A = P_x / P_y = MRS_B
* Production of both goods is competitive
    * MC_x = P_x, MC_y = P_y → P_x / P_y = MC_x / MC_y = MRT
* MRS_A = MRS_B = MRT

Second Welfare Theorem: Starting with any Pareto Efficient allocation, there is a distribution of ownership of inputs such that this allocation is also a competitive equilibrium

Fairness
* Equity → Redistribute ownership of inputs
* Efficiency → Use competitive markets
* How does society collectively determine what is fair?
        * How do we aggregate individual preferences into “social preferences”?

Majority Rule Voting
* There may not be a social ordering, and voting between pairs of alternatives leads to issues
* Social preferences don’t satisfy transitivity (Condorcet Paradox)

Aggregating Preferences Criteria
* Social preferences should be complete and transitive
* Unaminity: If everyone prefers x > y, then socially x > y
* Society’s ranking of x and y should depend only on individual rankings of x and y (independence of irrelevant alternatives)

Arrow’s Impossibility Theorem
* The only social mechanism that satisfies (1), (2), and (3) is dictatorship
* Sometimes the critera includes (4) non-dictatorship, in which case this theorem states no mechanism exists

Social Welfare Function
* A function w = f(u_1, u_2, …, u_n), where each u_i is a utility function, and w is increasing in each of the u_i’s
1. Utilitarian Welfare Function
    * “Greatest happiness for the greatest number of people”
    * w = u_1 + u_2 + … + u_n
2. Rawlsian Welfare Function
    * w = min{u_1, u_2, …, u_n}
    * Welfare only increases when we increase the lowest utility

Allocating Goods to Maximize Welfare
* Consider two people with utility functions and some number of a single good x
* Rewrite each utility function to solve for x
* Set the sum of these equal to the amount of good x
* Replace with functions of U_A and U_B to get an equation for the utility possibility frontier
* Slope of UPF = d U_A / d U_B

Utilitarian Case
* “Tangency” — Set slope of UPF = slope of welfare line (1)
* Substitute into UPF → Solve for U_A and U_B
* Substitute into utility functions to find x_A and x_B

Rawlsian Case
* Corner of Welfare line — U_A = U_B
* Substitute into UPF → Solve for U_A and U_B
* Substitute into utility functions to find x_A and x_B

Market Power: Ability to unilaterally influence the market price

Monopoly: Market with a single seller facing many buyers

Features of a monopoly:
* No close substitutes
* Barriers to entry

Barriers to Entry
* Natural Monopoly
    * Average cost falls continuously over a large range of output (economies of scale)
    * Large firm can undercut entrants due to lower cost per unit
* Ownership Barriers
    * Firm owns a significant share of an input resource
* Legal Barries
    * You cannot legally enter
    * Patents, Trademarks, Copyrights
* Network Barries
    * The value of the good increaases as the userbase increases
    * Social media, Online games
* Strategic Barriers
    * A firm creates an aggresive reputation that it will fight new entrants

Monopoly
* Profit Maximization
    * MR = MC
    * Note: In perfect competition, firms have no market power → output has no impact on price
        * MR = P = MC in a competitive market
    * MR \neq P in monopoly since output decisions affect market price
* Monopolist is still constrained by demand → increasing output means lowering price
    * MR is below the demand curve
    * P > MR = MC → P > MC

Finding Monopolist Output and Price
* Find Total Revenue → Find Marginal Revenue
* Find Marginal Cost
* Set MR = MC → Substitute Q into Demand function

Monopoly
* Q_m < Q^\star (monopolies produce less output)
* P_m > P^\star (monopolies charge a higher price)
* Ineffiency: P > MC → Deadweight loss

Inverse Elasticity Pricing Rule
* ( P - MC ) / P = 1 / | \varepsilon |
* LHS is markup, | \varepsilon| is elasticity

Price Discrimination
* A monopolist price discriminates if it charges more than one price
* A firm can price discriminate if
    * It has market power
    * It can prevent arbitrage (consumers selling to other consumers)

First Degree Price Discrimination (Perfect)
* Monopolist sells each unit at each consumer’s maximum willingness to pay
* MR = Demand Curve
* Consumer Surplus = 0, Monopolist captures all available surplus
* Monopolist produces efficient quantity → No deadweight loss

Second Degree Price Discrimination
* Two Part Pricing / Subscription & User Charges
* Start by finding the monopoly solution
* Now charge a fee equal to the consumer surplus
* Then, producer surplus is maximized and consumer surplus is 0
* Monopolist can do even better → Set price = MC → CS rises → Increase membership fee

Third Degree Price Discrimination
* Market Segmentation
* Charge a high price to consumers with low elasticity of demand
* Break market into “segments” (low |e| or high |e|) based on observable characteristics
* Business travellers are less price elastic than vacation travellers
* Coupons → only about 30% of customers use coupons
* Senior / Student discounts

Oligopy: Market structure with few firms → Firms must be strategic

Cournot Model
* Firms strategically choose quantities to produce (identical goods)
* Market price depends on total quantity
* Cournot Equilibrium → Each firm’s output is a best response to the other firms output
    * Nash Equilibrium

Finding Cournot Equilibrium
* Find the best responses for both firms in general
    * Write demand in general
    * Find Firm 1’s total revenue → get marginal revenue
    * Set MR = MC
    * This is the best response function
* Solve these together
    * Substitute one best response function into the other
* Find market price using both Cournot Equilibrium quantities

Cartel
* Firms stop competing and work together to maximize profit
* They would choose Q to be the monopoly quantity
* Market quantity reduces, Market price increases, firm profits increase
* The cartel typically does not survive since one firm could best respond to the monopoly quantity and make even more money
